      "markdown": "# ‚è≥ B10 ‚Äî Pret√©rito Imperfecto vs Indefinido (B1)\n\n**Goal:** Understand when to use **imperfecto** (background) vs **indefinido** (main events).\n\n---\n\n## ‚öñÔ∏è Difference in Meaning\n\n| Imperfecto | Indefinido |\n|---|---|\n| ongoing or repeated past action | completed, finished action |\n| background / description | main event / foreground action |\n| no specific end | specific time or date |\n| sets the scene | moves the story forward |\n\n**Example**\n- *Cuando era ni√±o, viv√≠a en Sevilla.* ‚Üí background (imperfecto)\n- *Un d√≠a fuimos al parque.* ‚Üí main event (indefinido)\n\n> üí° Imperfecto often goes with **mientras, siempre, normalmente, todos los d√≠as**, and indefinido with **ayer, una vez, entonces, de repente**.\n\n---\n\n## üìå Key Endings\n**Imperfecto**  \n-AR: aba, abas, aba, √°bamos, abais, aban  \n-ER/IR: √≠a, √≠as, √≠a, √≠amos, √≠ais, √≠an\n\n**Indefinido**  \n-AR: √©, aste, √≥, amos, asteis, aron  \n-ER/IR: √≠, iste, i√≥, imos, isteis, ieron\n\n---\n\n**Example narrative:**\n- *Hac√≠a sol y los p√°jaros cantaban. (imperfecto)*  \n- *De repente empez√≥ a llover. (indefinido)*\n\n> üìù Use imperfecto for scene, description, routine.  \n> Use indefinido for completed actions that move the story.\n",
